      • advance

        public int advance()
        Description copied from interface: Cycle
        Advances the current element to the next item in the sequence. The value returned is the number of actual positions by which the current element moved. If the sequence contains exactly one element then this will be zero (due to it being a cycle, the next element is also always the current element and the previous element). Otherwise, it will be one.

        This is equivalent to calling advanceBy(1).

        Specified by:
        advance in interface Cycle<E>
        Returns:
        the effective distance by which the current element was advanced

      • advanceBy

        public int advanceBy(int distance)
        Description copied from interface: Cycle
        Advances the current element by the specified distance. The value returned is the number of actual positions by which the current element moved and will be:
         Math.min(distance, distance % size())

        This method does nothing and returns zero if the specified distance is zero.

      • reset

        public void reset()
        Description copied from interface: Cycle
        Resets the current element to the first element in the sequence. The first element starts off as the first item added to an empty sequence. When that item is the "current" item and then Cycle.addFirst(Object) is invoked, the newly added item becomes the first element. If the first element is ever removed, the item after it is the first item.

        If the sequence is empty, calling this method does nothing.

        Specified by:
        reset in interface Cycle<E>

      • reverse

        public Cycle<E> reverse()
        Description copied from interface: Cycle
        Returns a view of this sequence in reverse order. The current element remains unchanged, but the sequence around it will be reversed. What would previously have been the next element will be the previous one in the returned view and vice versa. Calling Cycle.reverse() on the returned cycle will return the original sequence.

        Changes made to the view, including moving the "current" cursor, will be visible through the original cycle. For example, calling Cycle.advance() on the returned view has the same effect as having called Cycle.retreat() on the original sequence; calling Cycle.addFirst(Object) on the view has the same affect as calling Cycle.addLast(Object) followed by Cycle.retreat() on the original.

        Specified by:
        reverse in interface Cycle<E>
        Returns:
        a view of the cycle in reverse order
